definitions.definition: To bring into existence ; ( sometimes in particular: )
examples: You can create the color orange by mixing yellow and red.

subdefinitions.definition: To bring into existence out of nothing , without the prior existence of the materials or elements used.
To make or produce from other (e.g. raw , unrefined or scattered ) materials or combinable elements or ideas ; to design or invest with a new form, shape, function, etc.
examples: Couturiers create exclusive garments for an affluent clientele.

definitions.definition: To cause , to bring (a non-object) about by an action, behavior, or event, to occasion .
examples: A sudden chemical spill on the highway created a chain‐collision which created a record traffic jam.

definitions.definition: To confer or invest with a rank or title of nobility , to appoint , ordain or constitute .
examples: Henry VIII created him a Duke.   Last month, the queen created two barons.
Under the concordate with Belgium, at least one Belgian clergyman must be created cardinal; by tradition, every archbishop of Mechelen is thus created a cardinal.

definitions.definition: To be or do something creative , imaginative , originative .
examples: Children usually enjoy creating , never mind if it is of any use!

definitions.definition: In theatre , to be the first performer of a role; to originate a character.
To make a fuss , complain ; to shout.

main_definition: ( transitive ) To bring into existence ; ( sometimes in particular: )
secondary_definitions: ( transitive ) To cause , to bring (a non-object) about by an action, behavior, or event, to occasion .
( transitive ) To confer or invest with a rank or title of nobility , to appoint , ordain or constitute .
( intransitive ) To be or do something creative , imaginative , originative .
( transitive ) In theatre , to be the first performer of a role; to originate a character.
( UK , intransitive , colloquial ) To make a fuss , complain ; to shout.
